"[\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"GDPR Data Processing Agreement and Standard Contractual Clauses\",\n    \"heading\": \"GDPR Data Processing Agreement and Standard Contractual Clauses\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This GDPR Data Processing Agreement (\\\"DPA\\\") is between Controller and Proofpoint, Inc. (\\\"Processor\\\") and is appended to the Services Agreement. It sets forth the terms and conditions for Processor's receipt and processing of Personal Data from Controller, incorporating the Standard Contractual Clauses (SCC) annexed to EU European Commission Decision 2010/87/EU. Controller must complete, sign, and submit the DPA to privacy@proofpoint.com to be effective, and any revisions by Controller are rejected unless agreed by Proofpoint. The DPA terminates automatically with the Services Agreement or as otherwise specified.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"1.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Definitions\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This clause defines key terms: (a) All undefined terms have meanings from the GDPR and Services Agreement. (b) \\\"Data Protection Laws\\\" are applicable laws for processing Personal Data in connection with Proofpoint Products and Services. (c) \\\"Data Subject\\\" is the person to whom Personal Data relates. (d) \\\"Processing\\\" has the GDPR Article 4.2 meaning. (e) \\\"Subprocessor\\\" is any processor engaged by Proofpoint for Personal Data. (f) \\\"Supervisory Authority\\\" is an EU Member State public authority under GDPR.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"2.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Processing of Personal Data\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This clause establishes that Controller is the data controller/exporter and Processor is the data processor/importer for activities in Appendix 1. Controller warrants that its instructions comply with Data Protection Laws. The Services Agreement and this DPA define the subject matter, duration, nature, purpose, types of Personal Data, and categories of Data Subjects for processing, as detailed in Appendix 1. Controller is responsible for the accuracy, quality, and legality of Personal Data and its acquisition means. The Services Agreement and DPA constitute Controllerâ€™s instructions for processing and transferring Personal Data for Service provision.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"3.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Data Protection Impact Assessment\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Processor will provide reasonable cooperation and assistance to Controller for GDPR-required data protection impact assessments related to the Service, if Controller lacks access to relevant information and it's available to Processor. Processor will also assist Controller in cooperation or prior consultation with the Supervisory Authority as required by GDPR for tasks related to this Section 3.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"4.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Rights of Data Subjects\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Processor will promptly notify Controller, if legally permitted, upon receiving a Data Subject's request to exercise rights (access, rectification, restriction, forgotten, portability, objection, automated decision-making). Processor will assist Controller with appropriate technical and organizational measures to fulfill Controller's obligation to respond to such requests, insofar as possible considering the nature of processing.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"5.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Limited use of Personal Data & personnel\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Except as stated in the Services Agreement, Processor will not acquire rights in Personal Data. Processor and its affiliates will ensure that access to Personal Data by employees, agents, or contracted Subprocessors is strictly limited to those who need it for the Services Agreement, complies with data protection laws, and such individuals are bound by confidentiality obligations.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"6.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Subprocessors\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Controller generally consents to Processor using Subprocessors, including affiliates and third parties. Processor must have written agreements with Subprocessors that include data protection obligations no less protective than this DPA and remains fully responsible for their performance. A list of Subprocessors is on the Proofpoint Trust Site. Processor will notify Controller of changes via email if subscribed to the Trust Site, fulfilling GDPR and SCC notification requirements. Controller can object to new Subprocessors, and if accommodations cannot be made within 30 days, Controller may terminate the applicable service.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"7.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Special categories of Personal Data.\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Controller and its EU affiliates are solely responsible for complying with data protection and privacy laws, including those applicable to Personal Data requiring special handling or special categories like race, ethnicity, political opinions, health, or criminal convictions.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Security of Personal Data\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Processor must implement technical and organizational measures specified in Appendix 2 to secure Personal Data against accidental or unlawful destruction, loss, alteration, unauthorized disclosure, or access. The level of security considers the state of the art, costs, nature, scope, context, purposes of processing, and risks to Data Subjects. Access to Personal Data is limited to personnel necessary for the Services Agreement, who are committed to confidentiality.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"9.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Cooperation with Supervisory Authorities\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Upon Controller's request, Processor will provide reasonable cooperation and assistance for GDPR-required data protection impact assessments related to the Service, if Controller lacks access to relevant information and it's available to Processor. Processor will also assist Controller in cooperation or prior consultation with the Supervisory Authority regarding tasks related to Section 8 of this DPA as required by GDPR. Additionally, at Controller's expense, Processor will make reasonable efforts to acquire cooperation from Subprocessors in providing relevant information for Controller's GDPR obligations.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"10.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Personal Data Breach\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"In case of a known Security Breach (unauthorized use, disclosure, or acquisition of Personal Data compromising its security, confidentiality, or integrity), Processor will notify Controller in writing within 48 hours and provide updates. The notification will describe the breach, contact point, likely consequences, and mitigation measures. If all information isn't immediately available, initial notification will be followed by further details without undue delay.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"11.\",\n    \"heading\": \"International Transfer of Data\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Processor will comply with applicable Data Protection Laws for international transfers of Personal Data from the European Economic Area. Personal Data may be transferred to and processed in any country where Processor or its Subprocessors operate, including third party countries, solely for Service provision. All such transfers are governed by the Standard Contractual Clauses, incorporated as Schedule 2. Processor has compiled a Data Transfer Assessment (Transfer Impact Assessment) for transfers to the United States, available at the provided URL, in furtherance of Clause 14(b) of the Standard Contractual Clauses.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"12.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Governmental queries\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"In line with Clause 15 of the Standard Contractual Clauses, Proofpoint will not disclose Customer Data to third parties unless necessary for Service maintenance/provision or to comply with law/governmental order. If a governmental body demands sensitive Customer Data, Proofpoint will attempt to redirect them to Customer, potentially providing Customer's basic contact information. If compelled to disclose, Proofpoint will give Customer reasonable notice to seek a protective order, unless legally prohibited. Proofpoint, as a 'remote computing service,' deems it unlikely to be subject to government requests under FISA.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"13.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Verification and audit\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Pursuant to GDPR Section 28.3(h), Processor will provide Controller, upon reasonable written request and NDA, information about Personal Data Processing to demonstrate DPA compliance. Processor will allow onsite inspections by Controller or an independent auditor to verify DPA compliance if insufficient written evidence is provided, a Security Breach occurs, a Supervisory Authority requests it, or Data Protection Law mandates it. Inspections are limited to once per year unless mandated more frequently. All information and audits are subject to an NDA and must not compromise facility security. Each party bears its own audit costs.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"14.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Termination\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Controller acknowledges that suspension or termination of data processing under this DPA or Clause 18 of the Standard Contractual Clauses will follow the timeframe for cessation and deletion of personal data specified in the Services Agreement.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"APPENDIX 1 TO THE DPA\",\n    \"heading\": \"DETAILS OF THE PROCESSING\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This Appendix 1 outlines the details of Customer's Personal Data Processing as required by GDPR Article 28(3), or equivalent. It details specific Proofpoint products (Archive, CAD/CASB, Cloudmark, Continuity, DLP, Email Protection, Privacy, TAP, Digital Discover/Protection/Compliance, Email Fraud Defense, Essentials, Insider Threat Management SaaS, Isolation, Zero Trust Network Access, Proofpoint Security Awareness Training), specifying the types of Data Subjects, Categories of Personal Data processed (e.g., emails, metadata, account IDs, names, IP addresses, URLs, attachments, screen content), and the Processing Operations performed by each service (e.g., archiving, searching, blocking unauthorized access, scanning, filtering, routing, detecting fraud, collecting telemetry, rendering browsing sessions in virtual containers, network overlay, training rollout). It notes that product-specific DPA Appendices with more detail are available on www.proofpoint.com/legal/trust/dpa and only those relevant to licensed products are incorporated.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"1.\",\n    \"heading\": \"Subprocessors\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"A current list of subprocessors can be found at https://www.proofpoint.com/us/legal/trust.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"APPENDIX 2 TO THE DPA\",\n    \"heading\": \"SECURITY OF PROCESSING\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This Appendix 2 outlines the technical and organizational measures implemented by Processor to ensure an appropriate level of security for the Service, considering the state of the art, costs, nature, scope, context, purposes of processing, and risks to natural persons. Measures include: A. User Authentication (information security policy, security standards, procedures for user authentication/authorization, account management, monitoring failed logins, two-factor authenticated VPN for production access). B. Execution of backup copies (regular backup of configuration/report data, documented procedures). C. Computers and access terminals (secure VPN for employee access, anti-virus, centralized authentication, NDA and security code of conduct for new employees, business need-based access to production). D. Access logs (centralized logging of access attempts, automated reporting of unusual activity, account lockout policies, password complexity, logs of customer access to services, periodic review of access privileges, application event data retention). E. Telecommunication systems (redundant internet feeds in data centers). F. Instruction of personnel (annual security/awareness training, on-going training for security operations, organizational plan separating incompatible roles, clear role/responsibility definitions). G. Use of computers (restricted access to production networks for approved anti-virus systems, centralized authentication, acceptable use policies, NDA and security code of conduct for employees). H. Printing of data (customer data processed in memory, no printing in production data centers, print services disabled on production servers). K. Physical Access Control (Proofpoint maintains controls for co-location providers; hosting providers control for AWS, Azure, Google Cloud). L. Physical Security Measures for Data Centers (same as K). M. Access control to IT systems (unique user IDs, strong password requirements, role-based logical access, audit logging on VPN, real-time monitoring of audit logs). N. Access control to data (customer data not in Corporate Environment, role-based access, privileged access only for authorized personnel). O. Audit logging (on VPN and production environment systems). P. Implement least privilege access control (role-based access to Production Environment). Q. Security while transferring and processing (Customer data segregated from Corporate Environment, two-factor authenticated VPN, industry-standard firewalls, TLS encryption for web interfaces, LDAP for personnel access, patched OS, disabled unnecessary services, changed default passwords for servers). R. Security while transmitting data over public networks (all administrative access encrypted using TLS). S. Implementation and Operations phase controls (automated Service functionality, human intervention only for analytics/troubleshooting). T. Traceability of any access, change and deletion (role-based access, audit logging). U. Ensuring Compliant Data Processing (customer data automatically processed by Services, minimal manual processing). V. Ensuring Availability (high-availability infrastructure, Tier-3 data centers, on-site generators, Business Continuity Action Plan, distributed monitoring, firewalls, anti-virus on corporate devices). W. Data Separation (logical segregation using unique Client IDs). Additional product-specific DPA Appendices are available at www.proofpoint.com/legal/trust/dpa.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"SCHEDULE 2\",\n    \"heading\": \"Standard contractual clauses for the transfer of personal data to third countries pursuant to Regulation (EU) 2016/679 of the European Parliament and of the Council\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This schedule contains Standard Contractual Clauses (SCC) for the transfer of personal data from controllers to processors in third countries, adhering to Regulation (EU) 2016/679. These clauses ensure compliance, enforceable data subject rights, and effective legal remedies. They form an integral part of the DPA, are without prejudice to existing obligations, and define specific clauses that data subjects may invoke as third-party beneficiaries.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 1\",\n    \"heading\": \"Purpose and scope\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This clause specifies that the purpose of these standard contractual clauses (Clauses) is to ensure compliance with Regulation (EU) 2016/679 for personal data transfers to third countries. It identifies the data exporter (Controller, as listed in Annex I.A) and data importer (Proofpoint, Inc., as listed in Annex I.A) as the parties agreeing to these Clauses. The Clauses apply to personal data transfers detailed in Annex I.B, and the Appendix containing the Annexes is an integral part of these Clauses.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 2\",\n    \"heading\": \"Effect and invariability of the Clauses\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"These Clauses establish appropriate safeguards, including enforceable data subject rights and legal remedies, under Article 46(1) and 46(2)(c) of Regulation (EU) 2016/679. For data transfers between controllers and/or processors, they are standard contractual clauses under Article 28(7) of the Regulation, provided they are not modified except for selecting modules or updating information in the Appendix. This does not prevent additional clauses or safeguards that do not contradict these Clauses or prejudice data subjects' fundamental rights. These Clauses do not affect the data exporter's obligations under Regulation (EU) 2016/679.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 3\",\n    \"heading\": \"Third-party beneficiaries\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Data subjects can invoke and enforce these Clauses against the data exporter and/or data importer as third-party beneficiaries, with specific exceptions to certain sub-clauses. This is without prejudice to data subjects' rights under Regulation (EU) 2016/679.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 4\",\n    \"heading\": \"Interpretation\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Terms used in these Clauses that are defined in Regulation (EU) 2016/679 will have the same meaning. These Clauses will be read and interpreted in light of Regulation (EU) 2016/679 and will not be interpreted to conflict with rights and obligations provided therein.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 5\",\n    \"heading\": \"Hierarchy\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"In case of a conflict between these Clauses and related agreements between the Parties, these Clauses shall prevail.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 6\",\n    \"heading\": \"Description of the transfer(s)\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The details of the transfer(s), including categories of personal data and purposes, are specified in Annex I.B.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 7\",\n    \"heading\": \"Docking clause â€“ Not Applicable\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"This optional docking clause is not applicable.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 8\",\n    \"heading\": \"Data protection safeguards\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The data exporter warrants that it has reasonably determined the data importer can fulfill its obligations under these Clauses through appropriate technical and organisational measures. This section details obligations for transfer from controller to processor.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.1\",\n    \"heading\": \"Instructions\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The data importer will process personal data only on documented instructions from the data exporter, which can be given throughout the contract. The data importer must immediately inform the data exporter if it cannot follow these instructions.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.2\",\n    \"heading\": \"Purpose limitation\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The data importer will process personal data only for the specific purposes of the transfer as outlined in Annex I.B, unless further instructed by the data exporter.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.3\",\n    \"heading\": \"Transparency\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Upon request, the data exporter will provide a free copy of these Clauses, including the completed Appendix, to the data subject. The data exporter may redact confidential business information or personal data from the Appendix before sharing, but must provide a meaningful summary if the data subject would otherwise be unable to understand the content or exercise rights. The Parties will provide reasons for redactions if possible without revealing redacted information. This clause does not affect the data exporter's obligations under GDPR Articles 13 and 14.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.4\",\n    \"heading\": \"Accuracy\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"If the data importer becomes aware that received personal data is inaccurate or outdated, it must inform the data exporter without undue delay and cooperate to erase or rectify the data.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.5\",\n    \"heading\": \"Duration of processing and erasure or return of data\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Processing by the data importer will occur only for the duration specified in Annex I.B. At the end of processing, the data importer will, at the data exporter's choice, delete all personal data and certify deletion, or return all personal data and delete copies. Until deletion or return, the data importer must ensure compliance with these Clauses. If local laws prohibit return or deletion, the data importer warrants continued compliance and will only process data as long as required by law. This is without prejudice to Clause 14, especially the data importer's obligation under Clause 14(e) to notify if it believes it is subject to laws not in line with Clause 14(a).\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.6\",\n    \"heading\": \"Security of processing\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) Data importer and data exporter (during transmission) must implement appropriate technical and organisational measures to ensure data security, including protection against personal data breaches. They will consider encryption or pseudonymisation where feasible. Data importer must implement measures in Annex II and conduct regular checks. (b) Data importer will grant access to personal data only to personnel strictly necessary for contract implementation, management, and monitoring, ensuring they are bound by confidentiality. (c) In case of a personal data breach, data importer will take appropriate measures, notify data exporter without undue delay, providing contact details, breach description, likely consequences, and mitigation measures. Further information will be provided as it becomes available. (d) Data importer will cooperate with data exporter to help comply with GDPR obligations, especially regarding notifications to supervisory authorities and affected data subjects.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.7\",\n    \"heading\": \"Sensitive data\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"If the transfer involves sensitive data (racial/ethnic origin, political opinions, religious/philosophical beliefs, trade union membership, genetic data, biometric data for identification, health, sex life/sexual orientation, criminal convictions/offences), the data importer must apply specific restrictions and/or additional safeguards as described in Annex I.B.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.8\",\n    \"heading\": \"Onward transfers\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The data importer will only disclose personal data to a third party upon documented instructions from the data exporter. Onward transfers outside the EU are permitted if the third party is bound by these Clauses, benefits from an adequacy decision (GDPR Article 45), ensures appropriate safeguards (GDPR Articles 46 or 47), or if the transfer is necessary for legal claims or to protect vital interests. All onward transfers must comply with other safeguards under these Clauses, especially purpose limitation.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"8.9\",\n    \"heading\": \"Documentation and compliance\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) The data importer will promptly and adequately address data exporter's inquiries regarding processing under these Clauses. (b) Parties must demonstrate compliance, and data importer will maintain documentation of processing activities. (c) Data importer will provide necessary information to demonstrate compliance and, upon data exporter's request, allow/contribute to audits of processing activities at reasonable intervals or due to non-compliance indications. Data exporter can consider data importer's certifications. (d) Data exporter may conduct audits itself or through an independent auditor, including facility inspections with reasonable notice. (e) Parties will make information and audit results available to the competent supervisory authority upon request.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 9\",\n    \"heading\": \"Use of sub-processors\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) Data importer has the data exporter's general authorization for sub-processors from an agreed list. Data importer must inform data exporter in writing of any intended changes (additions/replacements) at least [Specify time period] in advance, allowing data exporter to object and providing necessary information. (b) When engaging a sub-processor for specific processing activities, the data importer must do so via a written contract with data protection obligations substantially similar to those in these Clauses, including third-party beneficiary rights for data subjects. Compliance with this clause fulfills data importer's obligations under Clause 8.8, and data importer ensures sub-processor compliance. (c) Data importer will provide a copy of the sub-processor agreement and amendments upon data exporter's request, with redactions for business secrets or confidential information. (d) Data importer remains fully responsible to data exporter for sub-processor performance and must notify data exporter of any sub-processor failure. (e) Data importer will agree to a third-party beneficiary clause with the sub-processor, allowing the data exporter to terminate the sub-processor contract and instruct data erasure/return if the data importer disappears, ceases to exist, or becomes insolvent.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 10\",\n    \"heading\": \"Data subject rights\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) The data importer will promptly notify the data exporter of any data subject request and will not respond without authorization. (b) The data importer will assist the data exporter in fulfilling its GDPR obligations to respond to data subjects' rights requests. Annex II will specify appropriate technical and organizational measures for this assistance, considering processing nature, scope, and extent. (c) The data importer will comply with data exporter's instructions in fulfilling these obligations.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 11\",\n    \"heading\": \"Redress\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) The data importer will transparently inform data subjects of a contact point for complaints and promptly address them. (b) In case of a dispute, the Party will amicably resolve the issue and cooperate with the other Party. (c) If a data subject invokes a third-party beneficiary right, the data importer accepts their decision to lodge a complaint with a supervisory authority or refer the dispute to competent courts. (d) Parties agree that data subjects can be represented by non-profit bodies per GDPR Article 80(1). (e) The data importer will abide by binding decisions under EU or Member State law. (f) The data importer agrees that data subject's choice does not prejudice their substantive and procedural rights to seek remedies under applicable laws.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 12\",\n    \"heading\": \"Liability\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) Each Party is liable to the other for damages caused by breaching these Clauses. (b) The data importer is liable to the data subject for material or non-material damages caused by breaching third-party beneficiary rights. (c) The data exporter is also liable to the data subject for material or non-material damages caused by itself, the data importer, or its sub-processor breaching third-party beneficiary rights, without prejudice to other GDPR liabilities. (d) If the data exporter is held liable under (c) for data importer's actions, it can claim back corresponding compensation from the data importer. (e) If multiple Parties are responsible, they are jointly and severally liable, and data subjects can sue any Party. (f) If one Party is held liable under (e), it can claim back corresponding compensation from other responsible Parties. (g) The data importer cannot use a sub-processor's conduct to avoid its own liability.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 13\",\n    \"heading\": \"Supervision\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) If the data exporter is not established in an EU Member State but falls under GDPR Article 3(2) (without needing an Article 27(2) representative), the supervisory authority of a Member State where relevant data subjects are located, as indicated in Annex I.C, will be the competent authority. (b) The data importer agrees to submit to the jurisdiction of and cooperate with the competent supervisory authority in ensuring Clause compliance, including responding to inquiries, audits, and complying with adopted measures, providing written confirmation of actions taken.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 14\",\n    \"heading\": \"Local laws and practices affecting compliance with the Clauses\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) Parties warrant that local laws/practices in the destination country (including disclosure requirements or public authority access measures) do not prevent data importer from fulfilling Clause obligations, based on laws/practices respecting fundamental rights and proportionality. (b) In providing this warranty, Parties considered transfer circumstances (processing chain, actors, channels, onward transfers, recipient type, purpose, data categories/format, economic sector, storage location), and relevant local laws/practices (including limitations/safeguards). (c) Data importer warrants it made best efforts to provide relevant information for assessment and will cooperate to ensure Clause compliance. (d) Parties agree to document and make the assessment available to the supervisory authority. (e) Data importer will promptly notify data exporter if it has reason to believe it is or has become subject to laws/practices not in line with paragraph (a) during the contract, including changes in law or disclosure requests indicating non-compliance. (f) Following such notification, or if data exporter otherwise believes data importer can't fulfill obligations, data exporter will identify appropriate measures. Data exporter will suspend transfer if appropriate safeguards cannot be ensured or if instructed by supervisory authority, and may terminate the contract concerning personal data processing under these Clauses. If terminated, Clause 16(d) and (e) apply.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 15\",\n    \"heading\": \"Obligations of the data importer in case of access by public authorities\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"15.1 Notification: (a) Data importer agrees to promptly notify data exporter (and data subject, if possible) if it receives a legally binding request from a public authority for personal data disclosure, or becomes aware of direct access by public authorities. Notification must include details of data requested, authority, legal basis, and response provided. (b) If prohibited from notifying, data importer will use best efforts to obtain a waiver to communicate information as soon as possible, documenting efforts. (c) Where permissible, data importer will provide data exporter, at regular intervals, with relevant information on requests received (number, type, authority, challenges, outcomes). (d) Data importer will preserve information from paragraphs (a) to (c) for the contract duration and make it available to the supervisory authority. (e) Paragraphs (a) to (c) are without prejudice to data importer's obligations under Clause 14(e) and Clause 16 to promptly inform data exporter of inability to comply. 15.2 Review of legality and data minimisation: (a) Data importer agrees to review legality of disclosure requests, challenging unlawful ones, and pursuing appeals. It will seek interim measures to suspend effects until judicial decision and will not disclose data until required by procedural rules. This is without prejudice to Clause 14(e) obligations. (b) Data importer will document its legal assessment and challenges, making it available to data exporter (if permissible) and supervisory authority. (c) Data importer agrees to provide the minimum amount of information when responding to disclosure requests, based on reasonable interpretation.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 16\",\n    \"heading\": \"Non-compliance with the Clauses and termination\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"(a) Data importer must promptly inform data exporter of any inability to comply with these Clauses. (b) If data importer breaches or cannot comply, data exporter will suspend personal data transfer until compliance is restored or contract terminated, without prejudice to Clause 14(f). (c) Data exporter may terminate the contract concerning personal data processing under these Clauses if: (i) suspension under (b) lasts for a reasonable time (one month) without compliance restoration; (ii) data importer is in substantial or persistent breach; or (iii) data importer fails to comply with a binding court/supervisory authority decision. Data exporter will inform the supervisory authority of non-compliance. If multiple Parties, termination right applies only to relevant Party unless agreed otherwise. (d) Personal data transferred before termination under (c) must be immediately returned or deleted at data exporter's choice, with deletion certified. Data importer must ensure Clause compliance until data is deleted/returned. If local laws prohibit return/deletion, data importer warrants continued compliance and will process data only as long as required by law. (e) Either Party can revoke agreement to these Clauses if the European Commission adopts an adequacy decision (GDPR Article 45(3)) covering the transfer, or if GDPR becomes part of the legal framework of the destination country, without prejudice to other GDPR obligations.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 17\",\n    \"heading\": \"Governing law\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"These Clauses are governed by the law of an EU Member State allowing third-party beneficiary rights. This will be: (a) the law of the country specified in the Services Agreement if it's an EU member state, or (b) the laws of the Netherlands if the Services Agreement is governed by a third country's laws.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"Clause 18\",\n    \"heading\": \"Choice of forum and jurisdiction\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"Any dispute arising from these Clauses will be resolved by the courts of an EU Member State. (a) Parties agree these courts will be (i) those specified in the Services Agreement if it appointed an EU member state court, or (ii) the Courts of Amsterdam if the Services Agreement appointed a third country court. (b) A data subject can also bring legal proceedings against the data exporter and/or data importer in their habitual residence's Member State courts. (c) The Parties agree to submit to the jurisdiction of such courts.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"EXPLANATORY NOTE: APPENDIX\",\n    \"heading\": \"EXPLANATORY NOTE: APPENDIX\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The Appendix must clearly distinguish information for each transfer or category of transfers, defining the roles of data exporter(s) and/or data importer(s). While not always requiring separate appendices for each transfer/contractual relationship, separate appendices should be used when necessary to ensure sufficient clarity.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"ANNEX I\",\n    \"heading\": \"LIST OF PARTIES\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"A. LIST OF PARTIES: The data exporter is the Controller identified on page 1 of the DPA. The data importer is Proofpoint, Inc., providing email and social media security, threat analytics, and security training. B. DESCRIPTION OF TRANSFER: Data subjects are Controller's employees, contractors, and those of its customers and vendors. Categories of data are identified in Annex 1 to this DPA; Controller will not transfer sensitive data to Proofpoint. Processing operations, including frequency, nature, purpose, and retention period, are identified in Annex 1. C. COMPETENT SUPERVISORY AUTHORITY: The Data Protection Authority of the Netherlands is identified as the competent supervisory authority according to Clause 13.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"ANNEX II\",\n    \"heading\": \"TECHNICAL AND ORGANISATIONAL MEASURES INCLUDING TECHNICAL AND ORGANISATIONAL MEASURES TO ENSURE THE SECURITY OF THE DATA\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The security, technical and organizational measures are described in Annex 2 to this DPA.\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"clause_id\": \"ANNEX III\",\n    \"heading\": \"LIST OF SUB-PROCESSORS\",\n    \"summarised_text\": \"The current list of subprocessors for the Service is available on the Proofpoint Trust Site at: https://www.proofpoint.com/us/legal/trust.\"\n  }\n]"